# Defining the age groups


age_betweens = [1, 25, 40, 60, float('inf')]
age_labels = ['18-24', '25-40', '40-60', '60+']

# Creating a new column 'Age_Group' based on age bins
df['Age_Group'] = pd.cut(df['Age'], bins=age_betweens, labels=age_labels, right=False)

# Displaying the first few rows to verify the changes

The duration of customer loyalty to the store is a crucial indicator of customer satisfaction and the establishment's ability to retain its clientele over time. The data reveals a diverse range of customer tenures, with approximately 69 customers having remained loyal for four years, indicating a significant portion of relatively recent but committed patrons. Conversely, the data also highlights a smaller group of 37 customers who have demonstrated exceptional loyalty, remaining customers for a remarkable 17 years. Understanding this spectrum of customer tenures allows businesses to tailor retention strategies accordingly, recognizing the varying needs and preferences of both long-standing and newer customers. Furthermore, identifying trends in customer tenure distribution facilitates targeted efforts to nurture and strengthen long-term relationships with the most loyal patrons, while also devising strategies to enhance retention among newer clientele.

The outcomes of the promotion responses are as follows: 236 customers chose to unsubscribe, indicating they didn't want any promotional updates or so.

On the other hand, 234 customers responded positively to the promotion, showing interest in the offer or message conveyed.

However, 206 customers chose to ignore the promotion entirely, neither responding positively nor opting out.

Understanding these response outcomes is essential for refining promotional strategies, tailoring messages to better resonate with the target audience, and optimizing the overall effectiveness of marketing campaigns.

In [129]:
def uniplot(df, col, title, hue =None):

    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.set_context('talk')
    plt.rcParams["axes.labelsize"] = 20
    plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 22
    plt.rcParams['axes.titlepad'] = 30

    temp = pd.Series(data = hue)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    width= len(df[col].unique()) +7+4*len(temp.unique())
    fig.set_size_inches (width, 8)
    plt.xticks (rotation=45)
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.title(title)
    ax = sns.countplot(data = df, x= col, order=df[col].value_counts().index, hue=hue, palette='bright')

plt.show()

Conclusion¶

1) Based on the age groups column i have made , it shows that higher percentage of customers are in their age of 40-60(i.e, 39.8%). This age group is the one with the highest email opt-ins. And also Female customers are higher than the males.

2) Highest number of returns made together by individuals are 5 and their satisfaction score being average of just 3 out of 5

3) Number of churned customers are higher than non-churned customers

4) As the ratings from the customers seem to be not high , that directly meaning that they wouldn't be getting a satisfactory product. This would normally lead to churns in customers & as it shows churns are more than non-churns
